GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 245
Short Title: Affordable Housing in Rural Areas. (Public)
Sponsors: Representative Willingham.
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Housing and Development, if favorable, Judiciary 1, if favorable, Rules, Calendar,
and Operations of the House
March 3, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO INCENTIVIZE THE DEVELOPMENT OF AFFORDABLE HOUSING IN
3 RURAL COMMUNITIES AND COUNTIES WITH HIGHER POVERTY LEVELS.
4 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
5 SECTION 1. G.S. 143-433.9 reads as rewritten:
6 "§ 143-433.9. Allocation.
7 (a) To provide for the orderly and prompt issuance of bonds the allocation of which is
8 managed under this Article, the Committee must follow formulas for allocating the following:
9 (i) the unified volume limitation, (ii) the state housing credit ceiling, (iii) the annual aggregate
10 limitation on the face amount of qualified public educational facility bonds, (iv) the limitation on
11 issuance of recovery zone facility bonds, (v) the limitation on issuance of recovery zone
12 economic development bonds, and (vi) the limitation on issuance of qualified energy
13 conservation bonds. The unified volume limitation for all issues of private activity bonds, other
14 than qualified public educational facility bonds and recovery zone facility bonds, in North
15 Carolina shall be considered as a single resource to be allocated under this Article. The annual
16 aggregate limitation on the face amount of qualified public educational facility bonds for all
17 issues in North Carolina shall be considered as a single resource to be allocated under this Article.
18 The Committee shall issue the following: (i) allocations of the unified volume limitation, (ii)
19 allocations of the state housing credit ceiling, (iii) allocations and reallocations of the aggregate
20 limitation on the face amount of qualified public educational facility bonds, (iv) allocation and
21 reallocation of the authority for issuance of recovery zone facility bonds allocated to the State,
22 (v) allocation and reallocation of the authority for issuance of recovery zone economic
23 development bonds allocated to the State, (vi) allocation and reallocation of authority for issuance
24 of qualified energy conservation bonds allocated to the State, and (vii) allocation of other
25 limitations on authority to issue bonds as may be directed by the Governor. The Committee shall
26 set forth procedures for making such allocations and in the making of such allocations shall take
27 into consideration the best interest of the State of North Carolina with regard to the economic
28 development, school facility needs, energy conservation, green initiatives, and general prosperity
29 of the people of North Carolina. In making the initial allocations for recovery zone facility bonds
30 and recovery zone economic development bonds, the Committee shall follow the formula
31 provided in section 1400U-1(a)(3) of ARRTA. In making the initial allocation for qualified
32 energy conservation bonds, the Committee shall follow the guidelines provided in section 54D
33 of the Internal Revenue Code of 1986. The Committee shall make all elective carryforwards of
34 the unused unified volume limitation, the annual aggregate limitation on the face amount of
*H245-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 qualified public educational facility bonds, recovery zone facility bonds, qualified energy
2 conservation bonds, and any other bonds or tax credits over which it has allocation authority on
3 behalf of the State. The Committee shall monitor the issuance of qualified energy conservation
4 bonds to ensure that not more than thirty percent (30%) of such bonds are used for purposes that
5 would be treated as private activity bonds under the Internal Revenue Code of 1986, as amended.
6 The Committee is authorized to establish a procedure to monitor whether the initial allocations
7 of recovery zone facility bonds or recovery zone economic development bonds to counties and
8 large municipalities pursuant to ARRTA will be utilized, for an allocation that will not be utilized
9 to be waived by notice to the Committee, and for the reallocation of the waived allocation to
10 other projects that qualify pursuant to ARRTA.
11 (b) In administering the low-income housing credit program, the Committee shall adopt
12 a Qualified Allocation Plan (the Plan) as required by 26 U.S.C. § 42(m) annually. Solely with
13 respect to the adoption of the Plan, the Committee is exempt from the requirements of Article 2A
14 of Chapter 150B of the General Statutes. The Committee, and any agency designated by the
15 Committee to administer the Plan, shall only adopt and administer the Plan if it incentivizes the
16 development and availability of affordable housing in rural communities and counties with
17 higher poverty levels. Prior to adoption or amendment of the Plan, the Committee shall:
18 (1) Publish the proposed Plan in the North Carolina Register at least 30 days prior
19 to the adoption of the final Plan;
20 (2) Notify any person who has applied for the low-income housing credit in the
21 previous year and any other interested parties of its intent to adopt the Plan;
22 (3) Accept oral and written comments on the proposed Plan; and
23 (4) Hold at least one public hearing on the proposed Plan.
24 (b1) When administering the low-income housing credit program and adopting a Qualified
25 Allocation Plan (the Plan) as required by 26 U.S.C. § 42(m) annually, the Committee, and any
26 agency designated by the Committee to the extent necessary to administer the Plan, shall, in the
27 interest of incentivizing the development of affordable housing in rural and impoverished
28 communities, use at least all of the following guidelines and criteria when determining how to
29 allocate tax credits under the Plan:
30 (1) The distance between a proposed site and surrounding amenities, including
31 grocery stores, shopping centers, and pharmacies, shall be calculated using a
32 radius and not by using actual road driving distance.
33 (2) When a proposed site is located in a municipality with a population of less
34 than 10,000 people, favorable consideration shall be awarded to proposed sites
35 that are located 10 miles and less from the amenities identified in the Plan.
36 (3) When identifying amenities, the Plan shall define grocery amenities as stores
37 that have grocery sections.
38 (4) When two proposed sites are "tied" under the scoring criteria of the Plan, the
39 proposed site located in the area with the highest poverty level shall be
40 awarded the tax credits under the Plan.
41 (c) In administering the allocation and reallocation of authority for issuance of qualified
42 energy conservation bonds allocated to the State and reallocated to any "large local government"
43 as defined in 26 U.S.C. § 54D(e), the Committee shall establish procedures (i) to monitor whether
44 the initial sub-allocations of qualified energy conservation bonds to large local governments will
45 be utilized by October 1, 2017; (ii) for the waiver and return to the Committee of sub-allocations
46 that will not meet the deadline imposed by this subsection; and (iii) for the reallocation of
47 returned sub-allocations for other projects or purposes that qualify under 26 U.S.C. § 54D(f) for
48 financing with qualified energy conservation bonds. The Committee shall also develop programs
49 described by 26 U.S.C. § 54D(f)(1)(A)(iii) and shall consider those programs along with other
50 eligible uses for qualified energy conservation bonds in determining the reallocation of unused
51 and returned qualified energy conservation bond allocation."
